{
  "doc_id": "14501",
  "text": "The relapse rate in patients with Type 1 AIP ranges from 30-50% [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] , while patients with Type 2 AIP typically do not relapse. Sah et al. have identified proximal bile duct involvement and diffuse swelling of the pancreas as risk factors for disease relapse [CITATION_3] . There remains some debate as to the ability of elevations in serum IgG4 levels to predict relapse. Patients who relapse are typically treated with a second course of corticosteroids [CITATION_4] . Given the relatively high relapse rates, some centers routinely continue maintenance corticosteroid therapy for up to three years [CITATION_5] . Kamisawa et al. have shown that this reduces relapse rates from 34 to 23%. Others advocate close monitoring and recurrent use of corticosteroids as needed, to minimize therapeutic side-effects. Further, the steroid-sparing immunomodulator, azathioprine, can be used to maintain remission after the first or second relapse. Pannala et al. reported that 30-40% of AIP patients will eventually need maintenance therapy to prevent recurrent relapses [CITATION_6] .",
